      "comments": {
        "1": "The Anglo-Indian Defence. Black gives White the opportunity to transpose into an Indian Defence and keeps control of e4.",
        "5": "Black is dearly trying to induce White to transpose into a King's Indian by playing d4, but as we shall see, that is not White's intention.",
        "8": "",
        "10": "Note that if White had played d4 here we would be in a main line of the King's Indian Defence.",
        "11": "Interestingly, the engine already thinks 6...c5 is a forced draw, after a line like 7. a3, 7. Rb1, 7. d3 or 7. O-O. After 6...Nc6, White has a slight advantage but not a winning one.",
        "13": "There is little more to be gained from holding back the central thrust much longer.",
        "15": "An odd maneouvre, and while not bad, it is not clear what Black intended with this move.",
        "16": "An unnecessary central thust. 9. f4, working on the already developed Kingside, is more effective."
      },
